{"batchcomplete":"","query":{"normalized":[{"from":"pinion","to":"Pinion"}],"pages":{"1006635":{"pageid":1006635,"ns":0,"title":"Pinion","revisions":[{"contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{About|a type of gear}} \n\n[[Image:Annular (PSF).svg|thumb|right|Pinion and annular gear]]\n[[Image:Rack and pinion animation.gif|thumb|right|Rack and pinion animation]]\n\nA '''pinion''' is a round [[gear]] used in several applications:\n\n*usually the smaller gear in a [[Gear train|gear drive train]], although in the case of [[John Blenkinsop|John Blenkinsop's]] ''[[Salamanca (locomotive)|Salamanca]]'', the ''pinion'' was rather large.<ref name=\"agma\">{{cite book|isbn=1-55589-846-7|oclc=65562739|title=Gear Nomenclature, Definition of Terms with Symbols|pp=72|id=ANSI/AGMA 1012-G05|publisher=[[American Gear Manufacturers Association]]}}</ref> In many cases, such as [[remote control]]led [[toy]]s, the pinion is also the drive gear.\n*the smaller gear that drives in a [[Degree (angle)|90-degree]] angle towards a [[Gear#Crown|crown gear]] in a [[Differential (mechanics)|differential drive]].\n*the small front sprocket on a chain driven motorcycle. \n*the round gear that engages and drives a rack in a [[rack and pinion]] mechanism and against a rack in a [[rack railway]].\n*in the case of [[radio-controlled car]]s with an [[RC_cars#Fuel_models|engine]] (i.e. [[RC_cars#Nitro-powered_models|nitro]]) this pinion gear can be referred to as a '''clutch bell''' when it is paired with a [[Clutch#Centrifugal|centrifugal clutch]].<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.nitrorc.com/articles/clutch.html\n| title = Clutch Tuning\n| author = Eric Perez \n| publisher = NitroRC.com\n| accessdate = 2010-01-29}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of gear nomenclature]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Gears]]\n\n{{wiktionarypar|pinion}}\n{{Gears}}\n\n\n{{engineering-stub}}"}]}}}}